
A Basic Model
=============

.. code:: python

    # First perform the necessary imports
    import pandas as pd
    import matplotlib.dates as md
    import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
    from gwtsa import *
    %matplotlib notebook

1. Importing the dependent time series data
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

.. code:: python

    # Import and check the observed groundwater time series
    gwdata = pd.read_csv('B58C0698001_0.csv', skiprows=11,
                         parse_dates=['PEIL DATUM TIJD'],
                         index_col='PEIL DATUM TIJD',
                         skipinitialspace=True)
    gwdata.rename(columns={'STAND (MV)': 'h'}, inplace=True)
    gwdata.index.names = ['date']
    gwdata.h *= 0.01
    oseries = 30.17 - gwdata.h  # NAP
    oseries.plot()

2. Import the independent time series
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

.. code:: python

    # Import observed precipitation series
    precip = pd.read_csv('Heibloem_rain_data.dat', skiprows=4, delim_whitespace=True, parse_dates=['date'], index_col='date')
    precip = precip.precip
    precip /= 1000.0  # Meters
    
    # Import observed evaporation series
    evap = pd.read_csv('Maastricht_E_June2015.csv', skiprows=4, sep=';', parse_dates=['DATE'], index_col='DATE')
    evap.rename(columns={'VALUE (m-ref)': 'evap'}, inplace=True)
    evap = evap.evap

3. Creating the time series model
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

.. code:: python

    # Initiate the base model
    ml = Model(oseries)
    
    # Add the precipitation data as explanatory variable
    ts1 = Tseries(precip, Gamma(), name='precip')
    ml.addtseries(ts1)
    
    # Add the evaporation data as explanatory variable
    ts2 = Tseries(evap, Gamma(), name='evap')
    ml.addtseries(ts2)
    
    # Add a constant
    d = Constant()
    ml.addtseries(d)
    
    # Add a noisemodel
    n = NoiseModel()
    ml.addnoisemodel(n)

4. Solving and plotting the model
~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~~

.. code:: python

    # Solve the time series model
    ml.solve()
